## .NET MAUI Shell Navigation with `IQueryAttributable`

### 1. Passing a simple string (Product ID)

**Navigate from ProductListPage:**
```csharp
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"{nameof(ProductDetailsPage)}?productId={product.Id}");
}
```

### 2. Passing a complex object

```csharp
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    var navParams = new Dictionary<string, object>
    {
        { "product", product }
    };
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync(nameof(ProductDetailsPage), navParams);
}
```

> **Key difference:** simple types use the `?key=value` query-string overload; complex objects use the `Dictionary<string, object>` overload.

---

### Receiving data with `IQueryAttributable`

```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _productId;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private Product _product;

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach 1: string parameter (arrives as string)
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var idObj))
        {
            ProductId = idObj.ToString();
            // Load full product from a service, etc.
        }

        // Approach 2: complex object (arrives as the original type)
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var productObj) && productObj is Product p)
        {
            Product = p;
        }
    }
}
```

### Wire it up

**Register the route and DI:**
```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs or AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute(nameof(ProductDetailsPage), typeof(ProductDetailsPage));

// MauiProgram.cs
builder.Services.AddTransient<ProductDetailsPage>();
builder.Services.AddTransient<ProductDetailsViewModel>();
```

**Bind the ViewModel to the page:**
```csharp
public partial class ProductDetailsPage : ContentPage
{
    public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        BindingContext = vm;
    }
}
```

### When to use which

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| **String query param** | Survives deep links / URIs; simple | Must reload data on target page |
| **Object via Dictionary** | No extra fetch needed; immediate | Not URI-serializable; tightly coupled |

A common pattern is to support **both** in `ApplyQueryAttributes` — use the object if available, fall back to loading by ID otherwise.
